{
  "texts": [
    "Λ k are Lorentz-like transformation functions applied to the k-th element of the value function V i, dependent on the reward threshold R i, and the divergence of the probability flux, with κ as a scaling factor for the probability amplitude.In this formulation, the summation terms introduce an additional layer of complexity, accounting for the cumulative impact of multiple retrieval outcomes on the learning process.",
    "The Lorentz-like transformations Λ k encapsulate the relativistic effects of information retrieval dynamics, offering a novel perspective on the adjustment of LLaMA's retrieval strategies in response to variances in accuracy and relevance.",
    "This comprehensive approach ensures a rigorous and nuanced adaptation of the model's behavior, enabling a highly sophisticated reinforcement learning environment.",
    "Start LLaMA Model AdaptationThe integration of the reinforcement learning algorithm into the LLaMA framework, as in Figure 1, requires a series of methodical adaptations, ensuring seamless synergy between the model's pre-existing linguistic capabilities and the newly introduced decision-making processes.",
    "This adaptation is not merely a superficial layering of functionality but a profound reworking of the model's architecture to assimilate the reinforcement learning paradigm fundamentally.A LLaMA (x; θ, D, u, κ) = F RL (E(x; θ), D, u, κ)(2)The above equation represents the adaptation function A LLaMA, where x denotes the input data, θ represents the parameters of the original LLaMA model, and E is the encoding function of the model."
  ]
}